TY  - JOUR
T1  - Of Risk Taking and the Personal Distribution of Income
AU  - Kanbur, S. M.
Y1  - 1979/08/01
PY  - 1979
DA  - 1979/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260792
DO  - 10.1086/260792
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 769
EP  - 797
VL  - 87
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper revisits the analysis of risk taking and income distribution pioneered by Friedman, but in an extended--general equilibrium--framework. The results of this paper cast doubt on the generality of many of Friedman's strong propositions. In particular, we find that the relationship between inequality and liking for risk is not necessarily monotonic. Nor is it the case that greater diversity in tastes for risk necessarily contributes to greater inequality. The paper also analyzes the effect of progressive taxation on national income and inequality in the context of risk taking.
AB  - This paper revisits the analysis of risk taking and income distribution pioneered by Friedman, but in an extended--general equilibrium--framework. The results of this paper cast doubt on the generality of many of Friedman's strong propositions. In particular, we find that the relationship between inequality and liking for risk is not necessarily monotonic. Nor is it the case that greater diversity in tastes for risk necessarily contributes to greater inequality. The paper also analyzes the effect of progressive taxation on national income and inequality in the context of risk taking.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260792
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260792
Y2  - 2024/03/22
