TY  - JOUR
T1  - Wage Indexing Rules and the Behavior of the Economy
AU  - Blanchard, Olivier Jean
Y1  - 1979/08/01
PY  - 1979
DA  - 1979/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260793
DO  - 10.1086/260793
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 798
EP  - 815
VL  - 87
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Explaining economic fluctuations by the existence of imperfect wage rules begs the question of why such rules are chosen in labor contracts. The form of wage rules is not exogenous but determined by cost and efficiency considerations. Fully contingent rules preserve efficiency but are costly to write and enforce. Noncontingent rules may lead to large inefficiencies. Actual rules, which index the wage only to the price level, may be the optimal compromise. This paper characterizes the equilibrium of an economy in which the form of wage rules is endogenous. It shows the effects of the distributions of exogenous shocks on the equilibrium distribution of output and the form of the rule. It then studies the role of policy in such an economy.
AB  - Explaining economic fluctuations by the existence of imperfect wage rules begs the question of why such rules are chosen in labor contracts. The form of wage rules is not exogenous but determined by cost and efficiency considerations. Fully contingent rules preserve efficiency but are costly to write and enforce. Noncontingent rules may lead to large inefficiencies. Actual rules, which index the wage only to the price level, may be the optimal compromise. This paper characterizes the equilibrium of an economy in which the form of wage rules is endogenous. It shows the effects of the distributions of exogenous shocks on the equilibrium distribution of output and the form of the rule. It then studies the role of policy in such an economy.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260793
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260793
Y2  - 2024/03/22
